author: MARY ELLEN WRIGHT | Staff Writer
title: 1777 Lancaster County fraktur valued at up to $35,000 on 'Antiques Roadshow'
text:
1 of 3 ANTIQUES ROADSHOW 
This Lancaster County fraktur baptismal document, dated 1777 and attributed to the Sussel-Washington artist, was appraised at as much as $35,000 on "Antiques Roadshow" Monday night. ANTIQUES ROADSHOW 
Appraiser Leigh Keno pointed out the interesting detail in the face of one of the figures on a Lancaster County fraktur appraised on PBS' "Antiques Roadshow." ANTIQUES ROADSHOW 
Appraiser Leigh Keno uses a pointer to note the Pennsylvania German fraktur was dated in November 1777 and in Bethel Township, Lancaster County. 1777 Lancaster County fraktur valued at up to $35,000 on 'Antiques Roadshow' Attributed to the Sussel-Washington artist, document is a baptismal record
